<font color="#FF0000">A RESPONSE</font><br>
<tt>Tue Dec 30  9:03:52 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I want to continue and clarify some things I said.<br>
I did not condem anyone for their guilt. I said that I saw no need for guilt. It is quite different. <br><br>
As to &quot;high moral superiority&quot;, I make no claims to that. I do claim to have made a moral judgement for myself that I still believe was correct. I said that all of us made choices, based on what we believed at the time, and in fact, I give credence to all the different choices that people made when faced with the limited and distorted knowledge available to thje American citizen. <br><br>
In my humble opinion, I see the War in Vietnam as being a war against agression on the part of the US (and prior to that the French). Objectively, The US soldier was fighting to protect the interests of US corporations and to maintain a US dominance in S.E. Asia. I do not think that the US soldier, or most US citizens believed this and that US soldiers fought for altruistic reasons. I think most soldiers went to fight believing that they were trying to protect democracy in Vietnam. I think that US soldiers believed they were fighting a communist invasion of Vietnam. I do not condemn soldiers for doing what they thought was helping people in a foreign land. <br><br>
My beef is with the US government, that waged a war of agression against Vietnam for corporate interests and used lies and distortions to bring thousands of US soldiers into harms way. I condemn the government for knowingly killing thousands of Vietnamese and US people for greed and avarice. It is the government and its policies that are the problem, not the poor folk (you and I, vets and non vets, vietnamese and Americans and others) who paid the price of war. 
